Kano State Acting Governor Nasiru Yusuf Gawuna yesterday commiserated with the Lebanese community and family of Tahir Fadlallah over the death the notable industrialist. Tahir Fadlallah, owner of Tahir Quest Palace in Kano State, had been sick in a hospital abroad for more than one year. It was gathered that his body would be flown in and buried in Kano on Saturday according to Islamic rites. “I received the news of the death of Mr. Fadlallah with shock,” the acting governor said in a statement signed his Chief Press Secretary (CPS), Hassan Musa Fagge, yesterday.   NYSC probes death of missing corps member     Ambulance officials rescue woman in labour, deliver her of…     Nollywood actress slumps, dies in Enugu church   Gawuna said the deceased entrepreneur had made remarkable contributions to the development of Kano State as a businessman and philanthropist, culminating in the solid and cordial relationship with the government and people of Lebanon. “He will be greatly missed. I therefore on behalf of Governor Abdullahi Umar Ganduje, the government and people of Kano State extend our condolence to the deceased’s family and his friends,” Gawuna said. The Acting Governor urged the family to take the businessman’s death with equanimity, describing death as inevitable for everybody. He prayed the Almighty Allah to bless the soul of the deceased and reward him with Jannatul Firdaus.